***** First Call for Papers ********
***** Submission deadline: May 29, 2009 *******=20

ICMI-MLMI 2009

Cambridge, MA, USA,=20
November 2-6 2009=20
sponsored by ACM SIGCHI=20

The Eleventh International Conference on Multimodal Interfaces and The Si=
xth=20
Workshop on Machine Learning for Multimodal Interaction will jointly take=
 place=20
in the Boston area from November 2-6, 2009. The main aim of ICMI-MLMI 200=
9=20
is to further scientific research within the broad field of multimodal in=
teraction,=20
methods and systems. This joint conference will focus on major trends and=
=20
challenges in this area, and work to identify a roadmap for future resear=
ch and=20
commercial success. ICMI-MLMI 2009 will feature a single-track main=20
conference with keynote speakers, panel discussions, technical paper=20
presentations, poster sessions, and demonstrations of state of the art=20=

multimodal systems and concepts. It will be followed by workshops.

Venue:
The conference will take place at the MIT Media Lab, widely known for its=
=20
innovative spirit. Organized in Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA, ICMI-MLMI=20=

2009 provides an excellent setting for brainstorming and sharing the late=
st=20
advances in multimodal interaction, systems, and methods in a city known =
as=20
one of the top historical, technological, and scientific centers of the U=
S.

Important dates:=20

  Workshop proposals March 1, 2009
  Special Sessions proposals March 1, 2009=20
  Paper submission May 22, 2009=20
  Author notification July 20, 2009=20
  Camera-ready due August 20, 2009=20
  Conference Nov 2-4, 2009=20
  Workshops Nov 5-6, 2009=20

Topics of interest:

Multimodal and multimedia processing:
  Algorithms for multimodal fusion and multimedia fission
  Multimodal output generation and presentation planning
  Multimodal discourse and dialogue modeling
  Generating non-verbal behaviors for embodied conversational agents=20
  Machine learning methods for multimodal processing

Multimodal input and output interfaces:
  Gaze and vision-based interfaces
  Speech and conversational interfaces
  Pen-based interfaces
  Haptic interfaces
  Interfaces to virtual environments or augmented reality
  Biometric interfaces combining multiple modalities
  Adaptive multimodal interfaces

Multimodal applications:
  Mobile interfaces
  Meeting analysis and intelligent meeting spaces
  Interfaces to media content and entertainment
  Human-robot interfaces and human-robot interaction
  Vehicular applications and navigational aids
  Computer-mediated human to human communication
  Interfaces for intelligent environments and smart living spaces
  Universal access and assistive computing=20
  Multimodal indexing, structuring and summarization

Human interaction analysis and modeling:
  Modeling and analysis of multimodal human-human communication
  Audio-visual perception of human interaction
  Analysis and modeling of verbal and non-verbal interaction
  Cognitive modeling of users of interactive systems

Multimodal data, evaluation, and standards:
  Evaluation techniques and methodologies for multimodal interfaces
  Authoring techniques for multimodal interfaces
  Annotation and browsing of multimodal data
  Architectures and standards for multimodal interfaces


Paper Submission:

There are two different submission categories: regular paper and short pa=
per.=20
The page limit is 8 pages for regular papers and 4 pages for short papers=
. The=20
presentation style (oral or poster) will be decided by the committee base=
d on=20
suitability and schedule.

Demo Submission:

Proposals for demonstrations shall be submitted to demo chairs electronic=
ally.=20
A two page description with photographs of the demonstration is required.=


Doctoral Spotlight:

Funds are expected from NSF to support participation of doctoral candidat=
es=20
at ICMI-MLMI 2009, and a spotlight session is planned to showcase ongoing=
=20
thesis work. Students interested in travel support can submit a short or =
long=20
paper as specified above.

